- Number nine?
- Not guilty.

1184
01:02:53.520 --> 01:02:55.689
- Number ten?
- Guilty.

1185
01:02:57.483 --> 01:02:59.526
Number eleven?

1186
01:02:59.610 --> 01:03:01.445
Not guilty.

1187
01:03:01.528 --> 01:03:03.030
Number twelve?

1188
01:03:03.948 --> 01:03:06.283
Number twelve.

1189
01:03:06.367 --> 01:03:07.868
Guilty.

1190
01:03:13.791 --> 01:03:15.876
The vote is now six to six.

1191
01:03:15.960 --> 01:03:19.129
Yeah, right.
And we go into extra innings here, huh?

1192
01:03:21.548 --> 01:03:26.053
Six to six. I'm telling you, some of you people
in here must be out of your minds.

1193
01:03:26.136 --> 01:03:27.972
A kid like that.

1194
01:03:28.055 --> 01:03:31.308
I don't think the kind of boy he is
has anything to do with it.

1195
01:03:31.392 --> 01:03:33.477
The facts are supposed to
determine the case.

1196
01:03:33.560 --> 01:03:35.729
Don't give me that!
I'm sick and tired of facts!

1197
01:03:35.813 --> 01:03:37.815
You can twist them any way you like.
You know what I mean?

1198
01:03:37.898 --> 01:03:40.484
That's exactly the point
this gentleman has been making.

1199
01:03:40.567 --> 01:03:43.487
I mean, you keep shouting
at the top of your lungs.

1200
01:03:45.155 --> 01:03:47.074
I'd like to be a few years younger.

1201
01:03:47.157 --> 01:03:49.076
That man gets on my...

1202
01:03:52.454 --> 01:03:55.290
- My, it's hot in here, isn't it?
- Do you want a drink of water?

1203
01:03:55.374 --> 01:03:59.086
No. No, thanks. Thanks.

1204
01:04:06.927 --> 01:04:08.721
It's gonna rain.

1205
01:04:08.804 --> 01:04:11.056
Well, how'd you figure that out, killer?

1206
01:04:12.307 --> 01:04:14.184
How come you changed your vote?

1207
01:04:14.268 --> 01:04:16.687
Well, it just seemed to me
there was room for doubt.

1208
01:04:16.770 --> 01:04:18.981
You haven't got a leg to stand on.
You know that, I hope.

1209
01:04:19.064 --> 01:04:22.067
I don't feel that way. There were
a lot of details that never came out.

1210
01:04:22.151 --> 01:04:25.696
- Yeah. Well, good luck.
- Oh, come on. You're like everybody else.

1211
01:04:25.779 --> 01:04:27.990
You think too much.
You get mixed up.

1212
01:04:29.241 --> 01:04:33.203
- You know what I mean?
- Now, listen. I don't think you have any right...

1213
01:04:33.287 --> 01:04:35.873
Loudmouth.

1214
01:05:28.592 --> 01:05:31.095
Look at that come down, will you?

1215
01:05:32.262 --> 01:05:34.139
You know...

1216
01:05:34.223 --> 01:05:36.725
this reminds me of a storm
we had last...

1217
01:05:36.809 --> 01:05:40.270
Oh, when was that?
November...

1218
01:05:40.354 --> 01:05:43.440
I don't know. Something.
It was quite a storm we had there.

1219
01:05:43.524 --> 01:05:45.901
It was right in the middle of a game.

1220
01:05:45.984 --> 01:05:48.612
We were behind 7-6...

1221
01:05:48.695 --> 01:05:51.281
but we just started to move the ball,
right off the tackle.

1222
01:05:51.365 --> 01:05:54.159
Started cutting right,
slash here and slash right in...

1223
01:05:54.243 --> 01:05:56.036
cut right through.

1224
01:05:56.120 --> 01:05:58.622
And...

1225
01:05:58.705 --> 01:06:00.916
We had this kid Slattery, you know?

1226
01:06:02.084 --> 01:06:05.462
A real... He was an ox.
You know, a real ox.

1227
01:06:05.546 --> 01:06:08.048
I wish I had another one just like him.

1228
01:06:08.132 --> 01:06:12.636
I forgot to tell you. I'm the assistant head coach
at the Andrew J. McCorkle High School.

1229
01:06:12.719 --> 01:06:14.805
- Oh, yeah?
- That's out in Queens.

1230
01:06:14.888 --> 01:06:17.641
And, anyway...

1231
01:06:17.724 --> 01:06:19.810
we're starting to move along real nice.

1232
01:06:19.893 --> 01:06:23.063
Their whole line is just...
they're just coming apart.

1233
01:06:24.356 --> 01:06:28.110
And it starts to come down
cats and dogs, just like this.

1234
01:06:28.193 --> 01:06:30.821
Just whoosh, you know, right down.

1235
01:06:32.114 --> 01:06:35.492
Well, that was murder, you know?

1236
01:06:35.576 --> 01:06:38.162
I swear, I nearly bawled.

1237
01:06:38.245 --> 01:06:40.581
You just... You couldn't go nowhere.

1238
01:06:41.832 --> 01:06:43.167
Well.

1239
01:06:58.807 --> 01:07:01.310
Hey, what is it with this fan here?
How come...

1240
01:07:09.067 --> 01:07:10.819
Hey! Huh?

1241
01:07:10.903 --> 01:07:14.198
Must have been on the same
switch with the lights.

1242
01:07:15.199 --> 01:07:18.368
Well, things are looking up here, huh?

1243
01:07:19.036 --> 01:07:20.537
Yeah, huh?

1244
01:07:25.375 --> 01:07:27.377
Boy. That's better.

1245
01:07:34.051 --> 01:07:35.552
Hey!

1246
01:07:35.636 --> 01:07:37.304
Two points.

1247
01:07:41.308 --> 01:07:43.310
Any of you guys ever go to the Garden?

1248
01:07:45.604 --> 01:07:48.482
That's a damn stupid thing to do.

1249
01:07:48.565 --> 01:07:50.734
Oh, I'm sorry, I...

1250
01:07:51.777 --> 01:07:53.153
You know?

1251
01:07:54.863 --> 01:07:56.365
Pardon me.

1252
01:07:57.449 --> 01:07:59.785
Well, how do you like it?
Even Steven.

1253
01:07:59.868 --> 01:08:02.246
Pretty surprising, isn't it?

1254
01:08:02.329 --> 01:08:03.830
Yes.

1255
01:08:05.624 --> 01:08:09.127
Say, that business before,
when that tall guy, what's-his-name,

1256
01:08:09.211 --> 01:08:11.922
was trying to bait me...
That doesn't prove anything.

1257
01:08:12.005 --> 01:08:14.591
I'm a pretty excitable person.

1258
01:08:14.675 --> 01:08:18.512
I mean, where does he come off calling me
a public avenger, sadist and everything?

1259
01:08:18.595 --> 01:08:22.099
Anyone in his right mind
would blow his stack, huh?

1260
01:08:22.182 --> 01:08:24.476
He was just trying to bait me.

1261
01:08:24.559 --> 01:08:26.561
He did an excellent job.

1262
01:08:29.356 --> 01:08:31.566
I'll tell you what I think.
We're going nowhere here.

1263
01:08:31.650 --> 01:08:34.194
I'm ready to walk into court right now
and declare a hung jury.

1264
01:08:34.278 --> 01:08:36.113
There's no point in this thing
going on anymore.

1265
01:08:36.196 --> 01:08:37.531
Yeah. I go for that too.

1266
01:08:37.614 --> 01:08:40.450
Listen, let's take it in to the judge and let
the kid take his chances with 12 other guys.

1267
01:08:40.534 --> 01:08:43.370
I don't think the judge will accept a hung jury.
We haven't been in here very long.

1268
01:08:43.453 --> 01:08:45.122
Well, let's find out.

1269
01:08:45.205 --> 01:08:46.915
I'm not in favor of that.

1270
01:08:46.999 --> 01:08:50.210
Listen. This kid wouldn't stand a chance
with another jury, and you know it.

1271
01:08:50.294 --> 01:08:53.130
Come on! We're hung. Nobody's gonna
change his vote. Let's take it inside.

1272
01:08:53.213 --> 01:08:55.424
You still don't think there's room
for reasonable doubt?

1273
01:08:55.507 --> 01:08:56.800
No, I don't.

1274
01:08:56.883 --> 01:08:58.176
Pardon.

1275
01:08:58.260 --> 01:09:01.513
Maybe you don't fully understand
the term reasonable doubt.

1276
01:09:01.596 --> 01:09:04.141
What do you mean I don't understand?

1277
01:09:05.225 --> 01:09:07.185
Boy, how do ya like this guy?

1278
01:09:07.269 --> 01:09:08.937
I'm tellin' ya, they're all alike.

1279
01:09:09.021 --> 01:09:11.857
They come over here, running for their life,
and before they can take a deep breath...

1280
01:09:11.940 --> 01:09:14.318
they're telling us
how to run the show, huh?

1281
01:09:14.401 --> 01:09:16.194
Boy, the arrogance of this guy.

1282
01:09:16.278 --> 01:09:20.866
Hey, all right. Let's stop
the arguing for about two minutes in here.

1283
01:09:20.949 --> 01:09:23.327
Now, who's got something
constructive to say?

1284
01:09:23.410 --> 01:09:26.955
I'd like to go over something,
if you gentlemen don't mind.

1285
01:09:27.039 --> 01:09:29.708
An important point for the prosecution
was the fact...

1286
01:09:29.791 --> 01:09:32.544
that after the boy claimed
he'd been at the movies...

1287
01:09:32.627 --> 01:09:34.629
during the hours
that the killing took place...

1288
01:09:34.713 --> 01:09:38.592
couldn't remember the names of the movies
or the stars who appeared in them.

1289
01:09:38.675 --> 01:09:41.178
This gentleman here has put up that point
in here several times.

1290
01:09:41.261 --> 01:09:42.721
That's correct.

1291
01:09:42.804 --> 01:09:44.681
It was the only alibi the boy offered...

1292
01:09:44.765 --> 01:09:47.267
and he himself couldn't back it up
with any details at all.

1293
01:09:47.351 --> 01:09:50.604
Putting yourself in the boy's place,
do you think you could remember details...

1294
01:09:50.687 --> 01:09:54.149
after an upsetting experience such as
being slapped in the face by your father?

1295
01:09:54.232 --> 01:09:57.444
I think so, if there were
any special details to remember.

1296
01:09:57.527 --> 01:10:00.697
The boy couldn't remember names of the movies
he saw because he wasn't there that night.

1297
01:10:00.781 --> 01:10:02.824
According to the police testimony
in court...

1298
01:10:02.908 --> 01:10:06.036
the boy was questioned by the detectives
in the kitchen of his apartment...

1299
01:10:06.119 --> 01:10:09.039
while the body of his father
was lying on the floor in the bedroom.

1300
01:10:09.122 --> 01:10:11.708
Do you think you could remember details
under those circumstances?

1301
01:10:11.792 --> 01:10:13.794
- I do.
- Under great emotional stress?

1302
01:10:13.877 --> 01:10:16.380
- Under great emotional stress.
- He remembered them correctly in court.

1303
01:10:16.463 --> 01:10:18.423
He named the pictures
and the stars who played in them.

1304
01:10:18.507 --> 01:10:21.676
Yes. His lawyer took great pains
to bring that out.

1305
01:10:21.760 --> 01:10:24.304
He had three months from the night
of the murder to the day of the trial...

1306
01:10:24.388 --> 01:10:26.014
in which to memorize them.

1307
01:10:26.098 --> 01:10:28.767
It's not difficult for a lawyer to find out
what played at a particular theater...

1308
01:10:28.850 --> 01:10:30.519
on a particular night.

1309
01:10:30.602 --> 01:10:34.231
I'll take the testimony of the policemen who
interrogated the boy right after the murder...

1310
01:10:34.314 --> 01:10:36.733
when he couldn't remember
a thing about the movies...

1311
01:10:36.817 --> 01:10:38.735
great emotional stress or not.

1312
01:10:38.819 --> 01:10:42.114
- I'd like to ask you a personal question.
- Go ahead.

1313
01:10:42.197 --> 01:10:45.450
- Where were you last night?
- I was home.

1314
01:10:45.534 --> 01:10:48.078
- How about the night before that?
- Come on! What is this?

1315
01:10:48.161 --> 01:10:49.496
No, it's all right.

1316
01:10:49.579 --> 01:10:52.124
I left the office at 8:30
and went straight home and to bed.

1317
01:10:52.207 --> 01:10:53.875
And the night before that?

1318
01:10:53.959 --> 01:10:56.378
That was Tuesday night?

1319
01:10:56.461 --> 01:10:58.463
The night of the bridge tournament.
I played bridge.

1320
01:10:58.547 --> 01:10:59.881
Monday night?

1321
01:10:59.965 --> 01:11:03.176
When you get down to New Year's
Eve 1954, let me know, huh?

1322
01:11:05.178 --> 01:11:07.139
Monday night?

1323
01:11:08.390 --> 01:11:11.393
Monday night, my wife and I went
to the movies.

1324
01:11:11.476 --> 01:11:13.103
- What did you see?
- The Scarlet Circle.

1325
01:11:13.186 --> 01:11:16.440
- It was a clever whodunit.
- What was the second feature?

1326
01:11:16.523 --> 01:11:19.151
The...

1327
01:11:19.234 --> 01:11:21.903
I'll tell you in a minute.
The...

1328
01:11:21.987 --> 01:11:26.158
Remarkable Mrs. something...

1329
01:11:26.241 --> 01:11:28.702
The...

1330
01:11:28.785 --> 01:11:31.455
Mrs. Bainbridge.
The Remarkable Mrs. Bainbridge.

1331
01:11:31.538 --> 01:11:34.291
I saw that. It's called
The Amazing Mrs. Bainbridge.

1332
01:11:35.584 --> 01:11:37.961
Yes. The Amazing Mrs. Bainbridge.
I think that's right.

1333
01:11:38.044 --> 01:11:40.547
Who was in The Amazing Mrs. Bainbridge?

1334
01:11:40.630 --> 01:11:44.301
Barbara...
Long, I think it was.

1335
01:11:44.384 --> 01:11:46.386
A dark, very pretty girl.

1336
01:11:47.721 --> 01:11:50.223
Ling or Long, something like that.

1337
01:11:50.307 --> 01:11:53.518
- Who else?
- I'd never heard of them before.

1338
01:11:53.602 --> 01:11:58.023
It was a very inexpensive second
feature with unknown...

1339
01:11:58.106 --> 01:12:01.234
And you weren't under
an emotional stress, were you?

1340
01:12:04.154 --> 01:12:06.281
No.

1341
01:12:06.364 --> 01:12:08.033
I wasn't.

1342
01:12:09.910 --> 01:12:11.661
I think the point is made.

1343
01:12:11.745 --> 01:12:14.498
Big point!

1344
01:12:14.581 --> 01:12:16.750
You can talk till your tongue
is draggin' on the floor.

1345
01:12:16.833 --> 01:12:20.921
The boy is guilty, period.
You know what I mean, my friend?

1346
01:12:21.004 --> 01:12:24.257
- Who's got those cough drops?
- They're all gone, my friend.

1347
01:12:26.259 --> 01:12:28.512
Oh, boy. Look at that rain.

1348
01:12:28.595 --> 01:12:30.972
There goes your ball game.

1349
01:12:31.056 --> 01:12:33.475
It's only a shower.

1350
01:12:33.558 --> 01:12:35.727
Besides, they got the infield covered.

1351
01:12:35.810 --> 01:12:38.980
Right. Say, could I see that knife
a second, please?

1352
01:12:41.775 --> 01:12:44.110
Well, we're still tied up six to six.

1353
01:12:44.194 --> 01:12:46.196
Who's got a suggestion?

1354
01:12:46.279 --> 01:12:48.281
It's five after 6:00.
Let's get some dinner.

1355
01:12:48.365 --> 01:12:50.825
Why don't we wait till 7:00,
give it another hour, huh?

1356
01:12:50.909 --> 01:12:53.036
Okay with me.

1357
01:12:53.119 --> 01:12:55.288
There's something I'd like to say.

1358
01:12:55.372 --> 01:12:58.917
I mean, it's been bothering me a little,
and as long as we're stuck.

1359
01:12:59.000 --> 01:13:02.879
Well, there was this whole business
about the stab wound and how it was made.

1360
01:13:02.963 --> 01:13:04.589
The downward angle of it, you know?

1361
01:13:04.673 --> 01:13:06.675
Don't tell me we're gonna
start with that again.

1362
01:13:06.758 --> 01:13:08.385
They've been over it and over it.

1363
01:13:08.468 --> 01:13:10.762
Well, I know they did,
but I don't go along with it.

1364
01:13:10.845 --> 01:13:14.849
Now, the boy was 5 feet 7 inches tall.
His father was 6'2".

1365
01:13:14.933 --> 01:13:17.102
That's a difference of seven inches.

1366
01:13:17.185 --> 01:13:19.854
It's a very awkward thing to stab down
into the chest of someone...

1367
01:13:19.938 --> 01:13:21.940
who's more than half a foot
taller than you are.

1368
01:13:22.023 --> 01:13:24.150
Give me that.

1369
01:13:24.234 --> 01:13:27.028
I'll give you a demonstration.
Somebody get up.

1370
01:13:28.405 --> 01:13:30.323
You...

1371
01:13:34.828 --> 01:13:37.539
I want you to watch this 'cause
I don't want to have to do it again.

1372
01:13:37.622 --> 01:13:40.375
I'll make myself about six
or seven inches shorter, okay?

1373
01:13:40.458 --> 01:13:43.587
- It's about right. Maybe a little more.
- Okay. A little more.

1374
01:13:51.386 --> 01:13:53.805
That's not funny.

1375
01:13:55.890 --> 01:13:59.728
Now, nobody's hurt. Right?

1376
01:14:00.395 --> 01:14:02.188
Right. Nobody hurt.

1377
01:14:05.650 --> 01:14:10.447
Now, this is the way I'd stab a man
who was taller than I was.

1378
01:14:10.530 --> 01:14:12.991
Look at the angle, down and in.

1379
01:14:13.074 --> 01:14:15.160
And this is the way it was done.

1380
01:14:15.243 --> 01:14:17.412
Now tell me I'm wrong.

1381
01:14:19.623 --> 01:14:23.043
- Down and in. I guess there's no argument.
- Hold it a minute, will ya?

1382
01:14:23.126 --> 01:14:24.961
Can you give me that?

1383
01:14:25.962 --> 01:14:27.881
Boy, I hate these things.

1384
01:14:27.964 --> 01:14:29.633
- Did you ever see a knife fight?
- No.

1385
01:14:29.716 --> 01:14:31.301
- You?
- No.

1386
01:14:31.384 --> 01:14:34.179
Anybody here ever see a knife fight?

1387
01:14:34.262 --> 01:14:37.057
Well, I have.
You know, on my back stoop...

1388
01:14:37.140 --> 01:14:39.476
the lot across the street, backyard.

1389
01:14:39.559 --> 01:14:41.978
Switchblades came
with the neighborhood where I lived.

1390
01:14:42.062 --> 01:14:45.315
It's funny I never thought of it before.
I guess you try to forget those things.

1391
01:14:45.398 --> 01:14:48.777
- How do you use a switchblade?
- Well, you'd never use it like this.

1392
01:14:50.528 --> 01:14:52.822
See, you use too much time
switching hands.

1393
01:14:54.574 --> 01:14:57.077
Here's how, underhanded.

1394
01:14:59.788 --> 01:15:02.832
Anyone who's ever used a switch knife
wouldn't handle it any other way.

1395
01:15:02.916 --> 01:15:05.543
- Are you sure?
- I'm sure.

1396
01:15:05.627 --> 01:15:07.462
That's why they're made
to open like that.

1397
01:15:07.545 --> 01:15:10.173
You'd say the boy
was pretty handy with a knife?

1398
01:15:10.256 --> 01:15:13.426
You think he could have made
the kind of wound that killed his father?

1399
01:15:13.510 --> 01:15:17.430
No. Not with the experience he'd had
all his life handling these things.

1400
01:15:17.514 --> 01:15:19.516
I feel he'd have gone
for him underhanded.

1401
01:15:19.599 --> 01:15:22.644
How do you know? Were you
in the room when the father was killed?

1402
01:15:22.727 --> 01:15:24.729
No. Neither was anybody else.

1403
01:15:24.813 --> 01:15:28.024
So what are you giving us all this
mumbo jumbo for? I don't believe it.

1404
01:15:28.108 --> 01:15:31.361
I don't think you can determine what type of
wound the boy might or might not have made...

1405
01:15:31.444 --> 01:15:34.072
simply because he knew
how to handle a knife.

1406
01:15:34.155 --> 01:15:36.491
What do you think?

1407
01:15:36.574 --> 01:15:38.660
- I don't know.
- What do you mean you don't know?

1408
01:15:38.743 --> 01:15:40.578
I don't know.

1409
01:15:44.791 --> 01:15:46.793
How about you?

1410
01:15:46.876 --> 01:15:50.630
I don't know about the rest, but I'm getting
tired of this yackety-yackin' back and forth.

1411
01:15:50.714 --> 01:15:54.175
It's gettin' us nowhere.
So I guess I'll have to break it up.

1412
01:15:54.259 --> 01:15:56.803
I change my vote to not guilty.

1413
01:15:56.886 --> 01:16:00.223
- You what?
- You heard me. I've had enough.

1414
01:16:00.306 --> 01:16:02.767
What do you mean you've had enough?
That's no answer!

1415
01:16:02.851 --> 01:16:06.813
Hey, listen. You just take care of
yourself, huh? You know?

1416
01:16:06.896 --> 01:16:10.859
He's right.
That's not an answer.

1417
01:16:10.942 --> 01:16:13.903
What kind of a man are you?

1418
01:16:13.987 --> 01:16:17.115
You have sat here and voted guilty
with everyone else...

1419
01:16:17.198 --> 01:16:21.453
because there are some baseball tickets
burning a hole in your pocket.

1420
01:16:21.536 --> 01:16:25.790
And now you've changed your vote because
you say you're sick of all the talking here?

1421
01:16:26.791 --> 01:16:28.251
Now listen, buddy!

1422
01:16:28.334 --> 01:16:33.006
Who tells you that you have the right
to play like this with a man's life?

1423
01:16:33.089 --> 01:16:35.592
- Don't you care...
- Now wait a minute!

1424
01:16:35.675 --> 01:16:39.679
- You can't talk like that to me!
- I can talk like that to you.

1425
01:16:39.763 --> 01:16:41.639
If you want to vote not guilty...

1426
01:16:41.723 --> 01:16:44.100
then do it because you are convinced
the man is not guilty...

1427
01:16:44.184 --> 01:16:45.977
not because you've had enough.

1428
01:16:46.060 --> 01:16:48.646
And if you think he is guilty,
then vote that way.

1429
01:16:48.730 --> 01:16:51.941
Or don't you have the guts
to do what you think is right?

1430
01:16:52.025 --> 01:16:54.277
- Now listen.
- Guilty or not guilty?

1431
01:16:55.069 --> 01:16:58.656
- I told you, not guilty.
- Why?

1432
01:17:00.325 --> 01:17:01.951
Look, I don't have to...

1433
01:17:02.035 --> 01:17:05.163
You do have to! Say it! Why?

1434
01:17:05.246 --> 01:17:07.707
All right.
I don't think he's guilty.

1435
01:17:17.217 --> 01:17:18.843
I want another vote.

1436
01:17:18.927 --> 01:17:21.429
Okay.
There's another vote called for.

1437
01:17:21.513 --> 01:17:24.390
I guess the quickest way is a show of hands.
Anyone object?

1438
01:17:24.474 --> 01:17:27.393
Okay. All those voting not guilty,
raise your hands.

1439
01:17:28.311 --> 01:17:33.483
One, two, three, four,
five, six, seven...

1440
01:17:36.319 --> 01:17:37.987
eight.

1441
01:17:41.908 --> 01:17:44.035
Nine.

1442
01:17:45.036 --> 01:17:50.041
All those voting guilty,
raise your hands.

1443
01:17:50.124 --> 01:17:52.502
One, two, three.

1444
01:17:52.585 --> 01:17:55.088
Well, the vote's nine to three
in favor of acquittal.

1445
01:17:56.089 --> 01:17:58.258
I don't understand you people!

1446
01:17:58.341 --> 01:18:00.510
I mean, all these picky little points
you keep bringing up.

1447
01:18:00.593 --> 01:18:03.930
They don't mean nothing!
You saw this kid just like I did.

1448
01:18:04.013 --> 01:18:07.517
You're not gonna tell me you believe
that phony story about losing the knife...

1449
01:18:07.600 --> 01:18:09.602
and that business
about being at the movies.

1450
01:18:09.686 --> 01:18:12.689
Look, you know how these people lie.
It's born in them.

1451
01:18:12.772 --> 01:18:14.816
I mean, what the heck.
I don't have to tell you.

1452
01:18:14.899 --> 01:18:16.860
They don't know what the truth is.

1453
01:18:16.943 --> 01:18:20.655
And let me tell you, they don't need
any real big reason to kill someone either.

1454
01:18:20.738 --> 01:18:22.490
No, sir.

1455
01:18:22.574 --> 01:18:25.618
They get drunk!
They're real big drinkers, all of 'em.

1456
01:18:25.702 --> 01:18:28.872
You know that.
And bang, someone's lying in the gutter.

1457
01:18:28.955 --> 01:18:31.958
Well, nobody's blaming them for it.
That's the way they are, by nature.

1458
01:18:32.041 --> 01:18:34.127
You know what I mean? Violent!

1459
01:18:34.210 --> 01:18:35.712
Where are you going?

1460
01:18:35.795 --> 01:18:38.798
Human life don't mean
as much to them as it does to us.

1461
01:18:39.799 --> 01:18:42.802
Look! They're lushing it up
and fighting all the time...

1462
01:18:42.886 --> 01:18:44.888
and if somebody gets killed,
so somebody gets killed!

1463
01:18:44.971 --> 01:18:46.347
They don't care!

1464
01:18:46.431 --> 01:18:48.641
Oh, sure, there's some good things
about 'em too.

1465
01:18:48.725 --> 01:18:50.685
Look, I'm the first one to say that.

1466
01:18:50.768 --> 01:18:54.063
I've known a couple who were okay,
but that's the exception, you know what I mean?

1467
01:18:54.147 --> 01:18:57.901
Most of 'em, it's like they have no feelings.
They can do anything.

1468
01:18:57.984 --> 01:19:00.570
What's going on here?

1469
01:19:00.653 --> 01:19:02.697
I'm trying to tell ya...

1470
01:19:02.780 --> 01:19:04.782
you're making a big mistake,
you people.

1471
01:19:04.866 --> 01:19:07.869
This kid is a liar!
I know it. I know all about them.

1472
01:19:09.579 --> 01:19:11.748
Listen to me.
They're no good.

1473
01:19:11.831 --> 01:19:14.167
There's not a one of 'em who's any good.

1474
01:19:16.210 --> 01:19:18.671
I mean, what -
What's happening in here?

1475
01:19:18.755 --> 01:19:21.007
I'm speaking my piece,
and you...

1476
01:19:22.216 --> 01:19:23.885
Listen to me.

1477
01:19:24.969 --> 01:19:26.429
I...

1478
01:19:26.512 --> 01:19:28.973
We're...
This kid on trial here, his type...

1479
01:19:29.057 --> 01:19:31.059
Well, don't you know about them?

1480
01:19:33.019 --> 01:19:36.481
There's a danger here.

1481
01:19:36.564 --> 01:19:38.650
These people are dangerous.

1482
01:19:38.733 --> 01:19:41.778
They're... wild.

1483
01:19:41.861 --> 01:19:43.780
Listen to me.

1484
01:19:43.863 --> 01:19:46.199
- Listen.
- I have.

1485
01:19:46.282 --> 01:19:49.285
Now sit down
and don't open your mouth again.

1486
01:19:53.206 --> 01:19:55.959
I was only trying to tell you.

1487
01:20:32.453 --> 01:20:36.749
It's always difficult to keep personal
prejudice out of a thing like this.

1488
01:20:37.875 --> 01:20:41.879
Wherever you run into it,
prejudice always obscures the truth.

1489
01:20:43.464 --> 01:20:45.842
I don't really know what the truth is.

1490
01:20:45.925 --> 01:20:48.845
I don't suppose anybody
will ever really know.

1491
01:20:50.138 --> 01:20:54.100
Nine of us now seem to feel
that the defendant is innocent.

1492
01:20:54.183 --> 01:20:57.186
But we're just gambling
on probabilities.

1493
01:20:57.270 --> 01:20:59.230
We may be wrong.

1494
01:20:59.313 --> 01:21:01.691
We may be trying to let
a guilty man go free.

1495
01:21:01.774 --> 01:21:03.234
I don't know.

1496
01:21:03.317 --> 01:21:05.319
Nobody really can.

1497
01:21:05.403 --> 01:21:07.780
But we have a reasonable doubt...

1498
01:21:07.864 --> 01:21:11.367
and that's something
that's very valuable in our system.

1499
01:21:11.451 --> 01:21:15.997
No jury can declare a man guilty
unless it's sure.

1500
01:21:17.457 --> 01:21:19.834
We nine can't understand...

1501
01:21:19.917 --> 01:21:22.628
how you three are still so sure.

1502
01:21:23.463 --> 01:21:25.465
- Maybe you can tell us.
- I'll try.

1503
01:21:26.841 --> 01:21:30.344
You've made some excellent points,
but I still believe the boy is guilty of murder...

1504
01:21:30.428 --> 01:21:32.138
and I have two reasons.

1505
01:21:32.221 --> 01:21:35.349
One, the evidence
given by the woman across the street...

1506
01:21:35.433 --> 01:21:38.061
who actually saw the murder committed.

1507
01:21:38.144 --> 01:21:40.730
As far as I'm concerned,
that's the most important testimony.

1508
01:21:40.813 --> 01:21:44.067
And two, the fact that she
described the stabbing by saying...

1509
01:21:44.150 --> 01:21:49.781
she saw the boy raise his arm over his head
and stab down into the father's chest.

1510
01:21:49.864 --> 01:21:51.908
She saw him do it the wrong way.

1511
01:21:51.991 --> 01:21:53.910
That's absolutely right.

1512
01:21:53.993 --> 01:21:56.579
Let's talk about this woman
for a moment.

1513
01:21:56.662 --> 01:21:59.749
She said she went to bed
about 11:00 that night.

1514
01:21:59.832 --> 01:22:03.419
Her bed was next to the window,
and she could look out while lying down...

1515
01:22:03.503 --> 01:22:07.590
and see directly into the boy's room
across the street.

1516
01:22:07.673 --> 01:22:10.301
She tossed and turned for over an hour,
unable to sleep.

1517
01:22:10.384 --> 01:22:14.555
Finally, she turned toward the window
at about 10 minutes after 12:00...

1518
01:22:14.639 --> 01:22:19.769
and, as she looked out, she saw the killing
through the windows of a passing el train.

1519
01:22:19.852 --> 01:22:22.563
She said the lights went out
immediately after the killing...

1520
01:22:22.647 --> 01:22:27.443
but that she got a good look at the boy
in the act of stabbing his father.

1521
01:22:28.444 --> 01:22:32.281
As far as I can see it,
this is unshakable testimony.

1522
01:22:33.032 --> 01:22:35.701
- Well, that's the whole case.
- What do you think?

1523
01:22:41.082 --> 01:22:42.750
How about you?

1524
01:22:44.377 --> 01:22:46.838
I don't know.

1525
01:22:46.921 --> 01:22:48.923
So much evidence to sift.

1526
01:22:49.006 --> 01:22:50.967
This is a pretty complicated business.

1527
01:22:51.050 --> 01:22:54.846
Frankly, I don't see
how you can vote for acquittal.

1528
01:22:54.929 --> 01:22:57.265
It's not so easy to arrange
all the evidence in order.

1529
01:22:57.348 --> 01:22:59.392
You can throw out
all the other evidence!

1530
01:22:59.475 --> 01:23:03.062
The woman saw him do it!
What else do you want?

1531
01:23:03.146 --> 01:23:05.022
- Yeah, well, maybe...
- Let's vote on it.

1532
01:23:05.106 --> 01:23:07.275
Okay.
There's another vote called for.

1533
01:23:07.358 --> 01:23:09.193
Anybody object?

1534
01:23:09.277 --> 01:23:12.321
All right. I'm changing my vote.
He's guilty.

1535
01:23:12.405 --> 01:23:14.824
Anybody else?
The vote is eight to four.

1536
01:23:14.907 --> 01:23:18.494
Why is this such a personal triumph
for you, this one vote?

1537
01:23:18.578 --> 01:23:22.039
Okay. I say we're a hung jury.
I say we take it in to the judge.

1538
01:23:22.123 --> 01:23:24.834
How about it?
I want to hear arguments.

1539
01:23:24.917 --> 01:23:27.420
You, you're the leader of the cause.
What about it?

1540
01:23:29.672 --> 01:23:31.507
Let's go over it again.

1541
01:23:31.591 --> 01:23:33.509
We've been over it again!

1542
01:23:33.593 --> 01:23:38.389
The boy in the gray flannel suit here is bouncin'
backwards and forwards like a tennis ball.

1543
01:23:38.472 --> 01:23:42.310
No point in getting nasty
and trying to turn this into a contest.

1544
01:23:44.270 --> 01:23:45.730
Okay.

1545
01:23:45.813 --> 01:23:48.858
Maybe we can talk about
setting some kind of time limit.

1546
01:23:48.941 --> 01:23:51.068
Yeah, once around for the deal, huh?

1547
01:23:51.777 --> 01:23:55.531
It's a quarter after 6:00.

1548
01:23:55.615 --> 01:23:57.575
Someone before mentioned 7:00.

1549
01:23:57.658 --> 01:24:00.036
I think that's a point at which
we might begin to discuss...

1550
01:24:00.119 --> 01:24:03.372
the question of whether
we're a hung jury or not.

1551
01:24:03.456 --> 01:24:05.124
Don't you feel well?

1552
01:24:06.459 --> 01:24:08.419
I feel perfectly well, thank you.

1553
01:24:08.502 --> 01:24:11.214
I was saying that 7:00
would be a reasonable time.

1554
01:24:11.297 --> 01:24:14.217
The reason I asked about that
was because...

1555
01:24:14.300 --> 01:24:15.885
you were rubbing your nose like...

1556
01:24:15.968 --> 01:24:18.638
Oh, I'm sorry for interrupting...

1557
01:24:18.721 --> 01:24:21.933
but you made a gesture
that reminded me of something.

1558
01:24:22.016 --> 01:24:24.060
I'm trying to settle something here.
Do you mind?

1559
01:24:24.143 --> 01:24:26.145
Well, I think this is important.

1560
01:24:27.230 --> 01:24:29.023
Thank you.

1561
01:24:29.106 --> 01:24:31.734
Now then,
I'm sure you'll pardon me for this...

1562
01:24:31.817 --> 01:24:34.737
but I was wondering why
you were rubbing your nose like that.

1563
01:24:34.820 --> 01:24:36.489
Oh, come on, will ya?

1564
01:24:36.572 --> 01:24:40.743
At this point, I happen to be talking
to the gentleman sitting next to you!

1565
01:24:40.826 --> 01:24:44.080
Now, why were you rubbing
your nose like that?

1566
01:24:44.163 --> 01:24:48.251
Well, if it's any of your business,
I was rubbing it because it bothers me a little.

1567
01:24:48.334 --> 01:24:49.961
I'm sorry.

1568
01:24:50.044 --> 01:24:53.923
- Is it because of your eyeglasses?
- It is.

1569
01:24:54.006 --> 01:24:55.758
Now can we get on to something else?

1570
01:24:55.841 --> 01:25:00.429
Your eyeglasses made those two deep
impressions on the sides of your nose.

1571
01:25:00.513 --> 01:25:02.682
I hadn't noticed that before.

1572
01:25:02.765 --> 01:25:06.269
- That must be annoying.
- It is very annoying.

1573
01:25:06.352 --> 01:25:08.271
Well, I wouldn't know about that.

1574
01:25:08.354 --> 01:25:11.691
I've never worn eyeglasses.
Twenty-twenty.

1575
01:25:11.774 --> 01:25:14.318
Listen, will you come on already
with the optometrist bit?

1576
01:25:16.237 --> 01:25:19.782
The woman who testified
that she saw the killing...

1577
01:25:19.865 --> 01:25:23.411
had those same marks
on the sides of her nose.

1578
01:25:24.412 --> 01:25:26.622
Holy smokes!
You know, he's right.

1579
01:25:26.706 --> 01:25:28.374
Please.

1580
01:25:28.457 --> 01:25:32.211
Just give me a minute,
and I'll be finished.

1581
01:25:32.295 --> 01:25:35.131
I don't know if anyone else
noticed that about her.

1582
01:25:35.214 --> 01:25:39.093
I didn't think of it then,
but I've been going over her face...

1583
01:25:40.136 --> 01:25:42.263
in my mind.

1584
01:25:42.346 --> 01:25:44.348
She had those same marks.

1585
01:25:45.349 --> 01:25:49.520
- She kept rubbing them in court.
- He's right. She did do that a lot.

1586
01:25:50.563 --> 01:25:55.234
This woman was about...
about 45 years old.

1587
01:25:55.318 --> 01:25:59.280
She was making a tremendous effort
to look 35...

1588
01:25:59.363 --> 01:26:01.574
for her first public appearance.

1589
01:26:01.657 --> 01:26:04.910
Heavy makeup, dyed hair...

1590
01:26:04.994 --> 01:26:08.873
brand-new clothes that should have
been worn by a younger woman.

1591
01:26:08.956 --> 01:26:10.624
No glasses.

1592
01:26:10.708 --> 01:26:12.376
No, women do that.

1593
01:26:12.460 --> 01:26:14.879
See if you can get the mental
picture of it.

1594
01:26:14.962 --> 01:26:16.797
What do you mean, no glasses?

1595
01:26:16.881 --> 01:26:19.592
How do you know whether she wore glasses?
Just 'cause she was rubbing her nose?

1596
01:26:19.675 --> 01:26:21.886
Now, she had those marks.
I saw 'em.

1597
01:26:21.969 --> 01:26:23.888
So what?
What do ya think that means?

1598
01:26:23.971 --> 01:26:27.183
- I'm getting so sick of your yelling in here!
- Come on. Forget it.

1599
01:26:27.266 --> 01:26:30.269
Hey, listen. Listen, he's right.
I saw them too.

1600
01:26:30.353 --> 01:26:33.481
I was the closest one to her. She had these...
these things on the side of her nose.

1601
01:26:33.564 --> 01:26:36.776
- What do you call those on the side?
- Well, what point are you making here?

1602
01:26:36.859 --> 01:26:40.738
She had dyed hair, marks on her nose.
Well, what does that mean?

1603
01:26:40.821 --> 01:26:45.117
Could those marks be made
by anything other than eyeglasses?

1604
01:26:48.704 --> 01:26:51.040
No, they couldn't.

1605
01:26:51.123 --> 01:26:53.125
I didn't see any marks!

1606
01:26:54.752 --> 01:26:56.462
I did.

1607
01:26:56.545 --> 01:26:59.090
Strange, but I didn't think
about it before.

1608
01:26:59.173 --> 01:27:01.300
Well, what about the lawyer?
Why didn't he say something?

1609
01:27:01.384 --> 01:27:04.303
There are 12 people in here
concentrating on this case.

1610
01:27:04.387 --> 01:27:06.472
Eleven of us didn't think of it either.

1611
01:27:06.555 --> 01:27:09.725
Well, what about the district attorney?
Do you think he'd pull a trick like that?

1612
01:27:09.809 --> 01:27:11.685
Have her testify without her glasses?

1613
01:27:11.811 --> 01:27:13.231
Did you ever see a woman
who had to wear glasses

1614
01:27:13.311 --> 01:27:15.731
and didn't want to because
she thinks they spoil her looks?

1615
01:27:15.815 --> 01:27:19.318
Okay.
She had marks on her nose.

1616
01:27:19.402 --> 01:27:23.072
I'm giving you that.
From glasses, right?

1617
01:27:23.155 --> 01:27:27.326
She didn't want to wear 'em out of the house
so people would think she's gorgeous.

1618
01:27:27.410 --> 01:27:31.997
But when she saw this kid killing his father,
she was in the house alone.

1619
01:27:32.081 --> 01:27:34.291
That's all.

1620
01:27:34.375 --> 01:27:38.379
- Do you wear glasses when you go to bed?
- No, I don't.

1621
01:27:40.089 --> 01:27:42.007
No one wears eyeglasses to bed.

1622
01:27:42.091 --> 01:27:45.094
It's logical to assume that she wasn't
wearing them when she was in bed...

1623
01:27:45.177 --> 01:27:46.929
tossing and turning,
trying to fall asleep.

1624
01:27:47.012 --> 01:27:49.348
- How do you know?
- I don't know! I'm guessing.

1625
01:27:49.432 --> 01:27:51.892
I'm also guessing that she probably
didn't put her glasses on...

1626
01:27:51.976 --> 01:27:54.103
when she turned
to look casually out of the window.

1627
01:27:54.186 --> 01:27:56.939
And she herself testified the killing
took place just as she looked out.

1628
01:27:57.022 --> 01:28:00.067
The lights went off a split second later.
She couldn't have had time to put them on then.

1629
01:28:00.151 --> 01:28:01.777
- Wait a second.
- Here's another guess.

1630
01:28:01.861 --> 01:28:05.948
Maybe she honestly thought she saw the boy
kill his father. I say she only saw a blur.

1631
01:28:06.031 --> 01:28:09.618
How do you know what she saw?
How does he know all that?

1632
01:28:09.702 --> 01:28:12.455
How do you know what kind of glasses
she wore? Maybe they were sunglasses.

1633
01:28:12.538 --> 01:28:15.166
Maybe she was farsighted.
What do you know about it?

1634
01:28:15.249 --> 01:28:18.502
I only know the woman's eyesight
is in question now.

1635
01:28:18.586 --> 01:28:24.717
She had to be able to identify a person
60 feet away, at night, without glasses.

1636
01:28:24.800 --> 01:28:27.178
You can't send someone off to die
on evidence like that.

1637
01:28:27.261 --> 01:28:29.263
Oh, don't give me that.

1638
01:28:29.346 --> 01:28:31.515
Don't you think the woman
might have made a mistake?

1639
01:28:31.599 --> 01:28:34.018
- No.
- It's not possible?

1640
01:28:34.101 --> 01:28:35.728
No, it's not possible.

1641
01:28:38.689 --> 01:28:40.608
Is it possible?

1642
01:28:41.734 --> 01:28:43.402
Not guilty.

1643
01:28:47.573 --> 01:28:50.242
Do you think he's guilty?

1644
01:28:50.326 --> 01:28:52.328
I think he's guilty.

1645
01:28:55.080 --> 01:28:56.749
Do you?

1646
01:28:59.627 --> 01:29:02.671
No. I'm convinced.

1647
01:29:02.755 --> 01:29:04.340
Not guilty.

1648
01:29:04.423 --> 01:29:06.217
What's the matter with you?

1649
01:29:06.300 --> 01:29:08.219
I have a reasonable doubt now.

1650
01:29:08.302 --> 01:29:09.845
Eleven to one.

1651
01:29:09.929 --> 01:29:12.848
Well, what about all the other evidence?
What about all that stuff?

1652
01:29:12.932 --> 01:29:15.017
The knife, the whole business!

1653
01:29:15.100 --> 01:29:18.020
Well, you said we could throw out
all the other evidence.

1654
01:29:23.776 --> 01:29:25.945
Well, what do we do now?

1655
01:29:28.948 --> 01:29:30.616
You're alone.

1656
01:29:30.699 --> 01:29:34.537
I don't care whether I'm alone or not!
It's my right.

1657
01:29:37.706 --> 01:29:39.875
It's your right.

1658
01:29:49.009 --> 01:29:51.428
Well, what do you want?
I say he's guilty.

1659
01:29:53.055 --> 01:29:56.392
- We want to hear your arguments.
- I gave you my arguments.

1660
01:29:57.393 --> 01:29:59.520
We're not convinced.

1661
01:29:59.603 --> 01:30:02.398
We want to hear them again.

1662
01:30:02.481 --> 01:30:04.483
We have as much time as it takes.

1663
01:30:10.155 --> 01:30:14.618
Everything, every single thing
that took place in that courtroom.

1664
01:30:14.702 --> 01:30:16.620
But I mean everything
says he's guilty.

1665
01:30:16.704 --> 01:30:19.164
What do you think,
I'm an idiot or something?

1666
01:30:20.833 --> 01:30:22.918
Why don't you take that stuff
about the old man?

1667
01:30:23.002 --> 01:30:26.171
The old man who lived there
and heard everything.

1668
01:30:27.840 --> 01:30:29.508
Or this business about the knife.

1669
01:30:29.592 --> 01:30:31.594
What? 'Cause he found another one
exactly like it?

1670
01:30:31.677 --> 01:30:35.014
The old man saw him
right there on the stairs!

1671
01:30:35.097 --> 01:30:37.933
What's the difference
how many seconds it was?

1672
01:30:39.101 --> 01:30:41.103
Every single thing.

1673
01:30:42.521 --> 01:30:45.691
The knife falling through
a hole in his pocket.

1674
01:30:45.774 --> 01:30:49.111
You can't prove
he didn't get to the door.

1675
01:30:49.194 --> 01:30:51.614
Sure, you can take all the time,
hobble around the room.

1676
01:30:51.697 --> 01:30:54.283
But you can't prove it!

1677
01:30:56.201 --> 01:30:59.830
And what about this business
of the el and the movies?

1678
01:30:59.913 --> 01:31:02.958
There's a phony deal
if I ever heard one.

1679
01:31:03.042 --> 01:31:07.254
I'll bet ya $5,000
I'd remember the movies I saw.

1680
01:31:07.338 --> 01:31:09.590
I'm telling ya,
everything that's gone on...

1681
01:31:09.673 --> 01:31:13.510
has been twisted and turned!

1682
01:31:13.594 --> 01:31:15.679
This business with the glasses?

1683
01:31:15.763 --> 01:31:21.310
How do you know she didn't have them on?
This woman testified in open court!

1684
01:31:21.393 --> 01:31:25.356
And what about hearing the kid yell, huh?

1685
01:31:25.439 --> 01:31:28.692
I'm telling ya,
I've got all the facts here.

1686
01:31:29.860 --> 01:31:31.737
Here.

1687
01:31:34.114 --> 01:31:36.617
Well, that's it!
That's the whole case.

1688
01:31:43.832 --> 01:31:45.417
Well?

1689
01:31:47.711 --> 01:31:49.713
Say something!

1690
01:31:54.843 --> 01:31:58.430
You lousy bunch of bleeding hearts.

1691
01:31:59.098 --> 01:32:01.016
You're not gonna intimidate me.

1692
01:32:01.100 --> 01:32:03.602
I'm entitled to my opinion.

1693
01:32:06.980 --> 01:32:11.276
Rotten kids.
You work your life out!

1694
01:32:16.115 --> 01:32:18.075
I can't keep...

1695
01:32:22.746 --> 01:32:24.415
No.

1696
01:32:28.293 --> 01:32:30.129
Not guilty.

1697
01:32:33.507 --> 01:32:35.175
Not guilty.

1698
01:32:38.178 --> 01:32:39.805
Not...

1699
01:32:50.357 --> 01:32:52.526
We're ready now.

1700
01:34:46.181 --> 01:34:47.850
Hey!

1701
01:34:52.187 --> 01:34:53.856
What's your name?

1702
01:34:53.939 --> 01:34:55.440
Davis.

1703
01:34:55.524 --> 01:34:57.442
My name's McCardle.

1704
01:34:59.778 --> 01:35:01.446
Well, so long.

1705
01:35:01.530 --> 01:35:03.031
So long.

